```c++
#include <vector>
#include <functional>

int main() {
  std::vector<int> elves;

  // Bind push_back to elves
  auto push_back_to_elves = std::bind(&std::vector<int>::push_back, &elves, std::placeholders::_1);

  // Call push_back through the bound function
  push_back_to_elves(1);
  push_back_to_elves(2);
  push_back_to_elves(3);

  // Display elves
  for (const auto& elf : elves) {
    std::cout << elf << ' ';
  }

  return 0;
}
```
Here, we use `std::bind` to create a callable object `push_back_to_elves` that will call the `push_back` method on the `elves` vector when it is called with an argument.

`&std::vector<int>::push_back` is a pointer to the `push_back` method of `std::vector<int>`. `&elves` is a pointer to the `elves` vector instance we want to bind to. We use `std::placeholders::_1` to specify the argument that will be passed to the `push_back` method when we call `push_back_to_elves`.

Finally, we call `push_back_to_elves` three times with the arguments 1, 2, and 3. This results in the elements 1, 2, and 3 being added to the `elves` vector. We then display the contents of the `elves` vector using a range-based for loop.

